passages.name: the Chronicle's website
passages.text:
In the beginning they were shamefully like giggling schoolgirls. Polzin's daughter, three years old at the time, didn't recognize her mother and shrieked when held. They wore jeans with their headscarves, went anywhere and did anything that the boys could do. Only when their local translater was raped did the two (and their respective papers) feel the first jitters of a sexual liability.

"She was quite forthcoming with the information that she was assaulted by a so-called 'freedom revolutionary,'" Polzin wrote. "But at a time like this, in a place like this, justice is scarce for women. Worst of all, there was nothing Cat or I could do to help except stand back and let her try to [[reenter life]]."

(left-hand page, bottom left corner)

[img[egypt]]

passages.name: end1
passages.text:
"In the end, it's all so simple," Polzin had written in one of her last articles. "Write like what you have to say matters. It usually does.

"Much love from home, [[BJP]]."

passages.name: Much love from home
passages.text:
The story went (at least, the story that Benjamin Polzin popularized did) that Benjamin P. and Bany M. met in the spring of '99, in a class on sexual violence against women and children. Benjamin couldn't remember much of the class, years later, or even who taught it--as a pre-law underclassman, he'd taken it to impress some girl he'd met at the registrar's office. That girl turned out to be one Catherine Van Meulin.

Bany Melendez and Benjamin Polzin were married in early 2005, while he was still stumbling his way through law school. The newspaper clipping, yellowed and faintly stained with coffee, showed a grinning girl with long black hair and almost white skin and a boy with a buzz cut that made his forehead look like Kubrick's monolith. When asked how he and Bany ended up together, Benjamin responded, "She was the only girl who survived my Brad Pitt [[phase]]."

(left-hand page, center right)

passages.name: Start
passages.text:
He saved every byline, every instance of "Bany J. Polzin," every one he could find, and a piece of each wound up on two pages of his daughter's scrapbook. Every sign-off ever:

[[Much love from Syria]]
[[Much love from Egypt]]
[[Much love from Lybia]]

passages.name: Much love from Lybia
passages.text:
They were at a bar in Paris, a few flights and a dangerous motorcycle ride from the Syrian border, when word came that Colvin and Ochlik were being held (that is, their corpses were being held) by the Assad government, more or less as hostages. Terrorists had killed them, the government said, with an IED filled with nails. 

You aren't going back there, Polzin's boss told her over the phone. You're coming home right now.

And without his support, the Daily Messenger pulled Van Meulin as well.

"It makes you wonder, sometimes," Polzin wrote in a follow-up article. "I'm incredibly, incredibly lucky to have such a friendship with Cat Van Meulin of the Daily Messenger. Cat is beyond a shadow of a doubt the most courageous person I know, and if there's anybody I want by my side in a [[war zone]] it's her."

(right-hand page, center of the bottom half)

[img[rosemarie-colvin]]

passages.name: damascus
passages.text: data:image/jpg;base64,

passages.name: Van Meulin's arms
passages.text: It wasn't until much much later that the autopsy reports were leaked. Bany Polzin, it was discovered, who had survived civil wars, wars on terror, and wars on women, had finally been done in by a cerebral aneurism. A swelling in the back of her brain, unnoticed for years, had finally exploded on live TV. The coroner's best guess was that she had probably died moments after putting her had on Van Meulin's arm. It had been her last [[conscious action|end1]].

passages.name: hrw
passages.text: data:image/jpg;base64,

passages.name: Much love from Syria
passages.text: In the bottom right corner he glued a picture of her that Cat Van Meulin of the Daily Messenger had taken in Syria. Like the one-eyed woman with a name like hers, Bany Polzin was herding war orphans out of a strike and into a basement somewhere. Colvin-Polzin-Colvin-Polzin. Except, against all odds, Polzin and Van Meulin, oldest of friends, made it home in [[one piece]].\n\n[img[kids]]

passages.name: television camera
passages.text:
"Bany and I have known each other for fifteen years," Van Meulin told the camera.

"Twenty," said Polzin.

"Sixteen, actually. Either way, we've been just about everywhere together. Any two papers would be lucky to have us, actually. Two reporters for the price of one." Here the camera began to zoom in on her face. "We've had some close calls over the years. It can get pretty intense, you know?"

Polzin put a hand on her arm, and, taking it as a sign of affection, Van Meulin patted it.

"I feel blessed," she said. "I really do. God has been so good to me. I've had so many amazing opportunities... And now, thanks to this scholarship, we're going to give those opporunities to a new generation of journalists and photojournalists."

"Maybe this is pessimistic," the anchor said, "I don't know, but is this the kind of opportunity you'd want for them? With the state of the world what it is and all?"

"The world has never been a perfect place," Van Meulin said. "It takes guts."

"What about you, Ms. Polzin?" asked the anchor, and the camera swung over to Bany Polzin. Polzin didn't say anything--she was looking down at the ground, her hand still on Van Meulin's arm and her mouth hanging open a little. Her face was growing more and more blue by the second.

"Ms. Polzin?" the anchor asked, a little more hesitantly. "Uh... Ms. Polzin?"

And Polzin crumpled into [[Van Meulin's arms]].

passages.name: one piece
passages.text:
When Polzin and Van Meulin went overseas in November 2011, Polzin left behind a husband, Benjamin, a six-year-old daughter and a two-year-old son. Van Meulin left a dog, which went to live with Benjamin.

"I thought my husband would kill me when I said I was going back," Polzin laughed in an interview for local news station MIFOX29. "Of course it's terrifying to go into a country with so much conflict, but a lot of the fear is for the family you leave behind. We always seem to forget. Looking back to Daniel Pearl, Ochilk and Colvin all of those, we see a lot of brave journalists, not afraid to tell the truth when it would cost their lives. We forget about their [[families]]!"

(website printout. left-hand page, upper left corner)

[img[Assad]]

passages.name: reenter life
passages.text:
"Rape," Polzin wrote in a particularly angry essay for the Sunday edition, "is the forgotten war crime. It's easy for us to count war in the bodies, the severed limbs, the bombed-out buildings and the missile craters. No one counts the men and women who are assaulted--the survivors least of all.

"This is also the only war crime where we still vilify the victim. No one asks the amputee why he continued to work when the rebels rolled through, or the parents of dead children why their kids were playing near the school that was shelled. So why is her rape still [[her fault|start]]?"

(left-hand page, almost hidden behind the story of Polzin's informant)

[img[hrw]]<<set $seenegypt = "yes">>

passages.name: families
passages.text:
The night before Polzin was due to fly back toward Syria for the second time in less than a year, she sat on the edge of her daughter's bed and read to her until one in the morning.

"I felt like a bear that night. I could sniff her all over and tell, yes, this is my cub. Now, I don't claim to be a particularly good mother--what kind of mom spends her child's developing years being shelled in the seige on Homs? But she hugged me and told me, I love you, Mommy." Just about broke my heart to be leaving her--leaving them--[[again|start]]."

(taped across the crease, just above her professional Chronicle photo)

[img[damascus]] <<set $seensyria = "yes">>

passages.name: war zone
passages.text:
They spent one last night in Paris, and, at Van Meulin's request, the band played Polzin's favorite song. They danced to Moon River until the stars came out.

"Dykes," decreed a radio pundit the very first time Polzin and Van Meulin appeared on national evening news. "Flaming dykes. Surely makes you pity her blueballed husband and those poor kids. God, what's the state of journalism coming to? Dykes at the Chronicle [sic], that fag Cooper at CNN... Makes me sick."

"I'm not sure why folks find it so terribly interesting, whether or not Cat and I are or aren't," Polzin said in a special by the Chronicle. I've always suspected it's the same reflex that makes adulterers so suspicious of [[their spouses]]."

(right-hand page, near the bottom corner of Polzin's photo)

[img[libya1]]

passages.name: uncharacteristic cynicism
passages.text:
Little Alenka wasn't even speaking sentences when Polzin and Van Meulin hopped two different planes to Paris, then worked their way down to Iraq. They just missed the execution of Hussein, but arrived right on time for the firestorm that surrounded the al-Tikriti execution.

"I'll admit it was particularly intense, after months of being at home with Lenka," Polzin later wrote. "One day you're rubber-banding the cupboard doors, and the next you're reporting on how a man's head popped off like a dandelion flower when he was hung. The learning curve was a particularly steep one."

And then, at the end of April, 2007, Polzin and Van Meulin broke the human interest story of a young gay man who'd been brutally beaten outside his own home. It was barely even an original story, more Polzin's answer to a GQ article she'd picked up at a US base. But the wheel of fate must have been spinning in her favor--in their favor--because just a few days later the Matthew Shepard Act was passed, and the story lit up the blogosphere like lightning. Just like that, the tiniest little niche opened up for Polzin and Van Meulin, the [[human interest girls]].

(folded into quarters and tucked behind her Chronicle picture)

passages.name: their spouses
passages.text:
Among the photos of war and the pictures of Polzin in her favorite tan suit was a single Polaroid. Van Meulin had taken it herself, in what looked like a darkened practice room--a piano could almost be seen behind in the background. Polzin and Van Meulin had their arms around each other's shoulders in the picture. Each grinned as wide as their faces allowed.

The picture was labeled "Bany and Cat--[[U. of M|start]]."

(right-hand page)

[img[libya2]]<<set $seenlybia = "yes">>

passages.name: ...Marie Colvin
passages.text:
Marie Colvin, whose story inspired Polzin's, was a real war correspondent. Brave and funny and one-eyed (she lost the other to an RPG explosion in Sri Lanka, early 2001), she specialized in Middle Eastern conflicts. She was the first foreign correspondent to interview Libyan ruler Muammar Gaddafi after the United States completed Operation El Dorado Canyon, a retalitory air strike following a 1986 bombing in Berlin.

[img[colvin]]

Ms. Colvin's final reports came from Homs, Syria, where she was covering the government's 2012 seige. She described to Anderson Cooper the death of a baby boy, and stated that the Syrian government lied when it claimed to be shelling only terrorist gangs. Shortly thereafter, she and French photographer Remi Ochlik were killed by an IED as they fled from a building being shelled by the Syrian Army.

Later in 2012 Ms. Colvin was awarded the [[Anna Polikovskaya Award|http://www.rawinwar.org/content/view/242/204/]] for women defenders of human rights in zones of conflict.

[[back|BJP]]

passages.name: Much love from Lebanon, Bany J. Polzin
passages.text: Polzin was friends with one of the anchors on the midday news team--what a surprise! Polzin was friends with everyone--and Van Meulin got a whole collection of photographs of her chatting with the crew, flaunting the plaque dedicating the Polzin and Van Meulin Scholarship for Excellence in Journalism as she hammed it up, and peering for the first time into the other end of a [[television camera]].\n\n(three small thumbnails, across the bottom of the left-hand page)

passages.name: phase
passages.text:
There were no pictures in the birth announcements of either of Polzin's children, so there were just two little clippings from the local paper. She was named Alenka Eileen, for her father's mother and her mother's dated taste in music. His name was Henry Aiden. He'd been a bit of an accident.

Polzin quit her job in January of 2006 to raise her daughter. She hadn't spent a lot of time overseas yet, only a few months in Kandahar while visiting the 205th Corps, but after just a few months of midnight feedings and colic she was already feeling down. She spent afternoons watching CNN with a baby in one hand and a bottle in the other, wondering with [[uncharacteristic cynicism]] what was really going on out there.

Meanwhile, Cat Van Meulin was mulling around in her hometown up north, snapping pictures of the aftermath at Dawson College. Although they were three thousand miles apart, they were both thinking the same thing--something had to change.

(outside bottom corner of either page)

passages.name: human interest girls
passages.text:
Very quietly, in December of 2008, Benjamin and Bany Polzin petitioned for divorce. Not long after Polzin went back to Gaza to cover the refugees fleeing Operation Cast Lead, and somehow or another the paperwork was misplaced. They still held hands when MIFOX29 interviewed them on December 27, 2008.

"It's scary to be having her go back," Benjamin Polzin, who'd only recently passed the bar and sent out feelers in search of openings for tax audit lawyers. "We'll definitely be praying for her stateside."

Bany, an admitted atheist, blew him a [[raspberry|start]].

(screencap, centered below Polzin's Chronicle picture)
